# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1892-cleveland-spiders-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1892-cleveland-spiders-season/1887-cleveland-blues-season] The **1887 Cleveland Blues** baseball team finished with a 39–92 record, last in the American Association during their debut season.
[src:1892-cleveland-spiders-season/1887-cleveland-blues-season] Organized by streetcar tycoon Frank Robison, the team played its home games at National League Park.
[src:1892-cleveland-spiders-season/1888-cleveland-blues-season] The **1888 Cleveland Blues** baseball team finished with a 50–82 record, sixth place in the American Association.
[src:1892-cleveland-spiders-season/1889-cleveland-spiders-season] Before the 1889 season, the Cleveland Blues switched from the American Association to the National League.
[src:1892-cleveland-spiders-season/1889-cleveland-spiders-season] They also earned a new nickname, the **Cleveland Spiders**, because so many of their players were very thin.
[src:1892-cleveland-spiders-season/1889-cleveland-spiders-season] They finished their first season in the National League with a 61–72 record, good enough for sixth place.
[src:1892-cleveland-spiders-season/1890-cleveland-spiders-season] The **1890 Cleveland Spiders** finished with a 44–88 record and a seventh-place finish in the National League.
[src:1892-cleveland-spiders-season/1890-cleveland-spiders-season] The team played six straight home games in Indianapolis, Indiana at Indianapolis Park between July 28 and August 2 against the Brooklyn Bridegrooms and New York Giants.
[src:1892-cleveland-spiders-season/1890-cleveland-spiders-season] It was a former Sunday-games ballpark of the Indianapolis Hoosiers who had folded at the end of the previous season.
[src:1892-cleveland-spiders-season/1891-cleveland-spiders-season] The **1891 Cleveland Spiders season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1892-cleveland-spiders-season/1891-cleveland-spiders-season] They finished with a 65–74 record and a fifth-place finish in the National League.
[src:1892-cleveland-spiders-season/1891-cleveland-spiders-season] The Spiders moved to a new ballpark in 1891.
[src:1892-cleveland-spiders-season/1891-cleveland-spiders-season] League Park was financed by Spiders owner Frank Robison, and it would be the team's home for the remainder of their existence.
[src:1892-cleveland-spiders-season/1891-cleveland-spiders-season] It would also be home to the Cleveland Indians.
[src:1892-cleveland-spiders-season/1891-cleveland-spiders-season] Patsy Tebeau, the team's starting third baseman, was named manager midway through the season.
[src:1892-cleveland-spiders-season/1891-cleveland-spiders-season] He remained the Spiders manager until his contract was reassigned to the St.
[src:1892-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-baltimore-orioles-season] The **1892 Baltimore Orioles season** was the first season that the professional baseball team known as the Baltimore Orioles competed in the National League, following the demise of the American Association.
[src:1892-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-baltimore-orioles-season] In a split season schedule, the Orioles finished last in the first half of the season and 10th in the second half.
[src:1892-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-baltimore-orioles-season] Overall, the team had a record of 46–101, worst in the 12-team National League.
[src:1892-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-baltimore-orioles-season] The 19th-century Orioles franchise is not the Baltimore Orioles franchise that has competed in the American League since 1954.
[src:1892-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-boston-beaneaters-season] The **1892 Boston Beaneaters season** was the 22nd season of the franchise.
[src:1892-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-boston-beaneaters-season] The Beaneaters won their second straight and fifth overall National League pennant.
[src:1892-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-boston-beaneaters-season] In the league's first split season, the Beaneaters finished first in the first half, and three games behind the Cleveland Spiders in the second half.
[src:1892-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-boston-beaneaters-season] After the season, the two teams played a "World's Championship Series", which the Beaneaters won, five games to none (with one tie).
[src:1892-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-boston-beaneaters-season] The National League did not play another split season until 1981.
[src:1892-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-boston-beaneaters-season] The Boston Beaneaters, first-half champions, played the second-half champion Cleveland Spiders in a best-of-nine postseason series.
[src:1892-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-boston-beaneaters-season] After a 0–0 tie in the opener, called on account of darkness after 11 innings, Boston defeated Cleveland five games in a row for a sweep.
[src:1892-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-boston-beaneaters-season] Hall of Famer Hugh Duffy batted .462 with nine runs batted in and six extra-base hits including a home run.
[src:1892-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-cleveland-spiders-season] The **1892 Cleveland Spiders**, led by star pitcher Cy Young, finished with a 93–56 overall record, second-best in the National League.
[src:1892-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-cleveland-spiders-season] In the first split season in Major League Baseball history, the Spiders finished in fifth place during the first half of the season, and in first place during the second half.
[src:1892-cleveland-spiders-season/1892-cleveland-spiders-season] After the season, they played against the first-half champions, the Boston Beaneaters, in the "World's Championship Series", which the Spiders lost, five games to none (with one tie).
